  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and imprisonment. The specific penalties depend on the circumstances, but generally involve:\n\n1. Monetary fines:\n- Substantial financial penalties, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n\n2. Criminal imprisonment:\n- Typically 10-20 years in federal prison\n- Potential sentences can increase for more complex or large-scale operations\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Supervised release after imprisonment\n\nThe exact penalties are determined by factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific type of money laundering\n- Whether it's a first or repeat offense\n- Intent and circumstances of the crime\n\nProsecution is typically handled by federal agencies like the Department of Justice.\n\nNote: This is general legal information, not specific legal advice. Actual penalties can vary based on precise legal circumstances.",
